<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,906,2011]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,1194,1219]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[346,443,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURES 133–143" captionStartId="115.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@115.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="115" captionText="FIGURES 133–143. leaf mines; 133: Liriomyza arctii Spencer in Ƒerbesina alternifolia; 134: L. asclepiadis Spencer in Asclepias exaltata; 135: L. baccharidis Spencer in Erigeron annuus, lower surface (left) and upper surface (right); 136: L. blechi Spencer in Plantago virginica; 137: L. brassicae (Riley) in Lepidium virginicum; 138: L. eupatoriella Spencer in Ageratina altissima; 139: L. eupatoriella in Ƒernonia baldwinii; 140: L. eupatorii (Kaltenbach) in Baccharis halimifolia; 141: L. fricki Spencer in Trifolium repens; 142: L. galiivora (Spencer) in Galium circaezans (transmitted light); 143: L. ivorcutleri spec. nov. in Silphium perfoliatum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452947/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 134</figureCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation box="[460,634,1194,1219]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer (1969)</bibRefCitation>
originally described the mine as an irregular, partly interparenchymal blotch with frass in scattered black grains, frequently with numerous larvae in a single leaf. 
<bibRefCitation pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal (1986)</bibRefCitation>
described it as a small, predominantly regular blotch mine, with greenish diffused frass. It is possible that the discrepancy has something to do with Spencer’s including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer (Spencer &amp; Steyskal" authorityYear="1986" box="[892,1092,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subasclepiadis">
<emphasis box="[892,1092,1302,1327]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. subasclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his original concept of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asclepiadis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. asclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but our own observations indicate that the mine can differ depending on the host species. The mines we observed on 
<taxonomicName box="[337,562,1374,1399]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incarnata">
<emphasis box="[337,562,1374,1399]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Asclepias incarnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were small, irregular, and largely interparenchymal, appearing greenish with associated reddish discoloration, sometimes mottled with whitish on the upper surface. There was little evident frass. The mines on 
<emphasis box="[383,636,1446,1471]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName box="[383,509,1446,1471]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exaltata">
<collectingRegion box="[383,403,1447,1470]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. exaltata
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[522,636,1447,1470]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="syriaca">
<collectingRegion box="[522,542,1447,1470]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. syriaca
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walter (Spencer" authorityYear="1969" box="[694,799,1446,1471]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis box="[694,799,1446,1471]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[694,714,1447,1470]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. viridis
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are entirely on the upper surface, whitish suffused with green to varying degrees, with dark green to black frass in scattered grains or irregular lumps. Mines are at least sometimes initially linear, but this portion is almost always obliterated by the blotch before long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,821,1554,1579]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,906,2011]" box="[199,821,1554,1579]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1554,1579]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Puparium.</emphasis>
Yellow to orange; formed outside the mine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,906,2011]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1590,1615]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,419,1591,1615]" name="United States of America" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">USA</collectingCountry>
: IN, *KS, MA, NH, NY; 
<collectingCountry box="[702,791,1590,1615]" name="Canada" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Canada</collectingCountry>
: ON, QC. The record of ID (
<bibRefCitation box="[1109,1278,1590,1615]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref102002" refString="Lonsdale, O. (2017) The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of Canada &amp; Alaska. Zootaxa, 4234 (1), 1 - 156. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4234.1.1" type="journal article">Lonsdale 2017</bibRefCitation>
) is erroneous; IN was intended (
<bibRefCitation box="[349,508,1626,1651]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer 1969</bibRefCitation>
). See comments for other (tentative) distribution data.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,906,2011]" lastBlockId="46.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1662,1687]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Comments.</emphasis>
The record of this species from 
<taxonomicName authority="Decne." authorityName="Decne." box="[718,1032,1662,1687]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ovalifolia">
<emphasis box="[718,943,1662,1687]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Asclepias ovalifolia</emphasis>
Decne.
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingRegion box="[1072,1190,1662,1687]" country="United States of America" name="Minnesota" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Minnesota</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal 1986</bibRefCitation>
) is based on empty leaf mines. To this we can add 
<taxonomicName authority="(A. Gray) Vail" authorityName="(A. Gray) Vail" box="[789,1153,1698,1723]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subverticillata">
<emphasis box="[789,983,1698,1723]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[789,809,1699,1722]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. subverticillata
</emphasis>
(
<collectingRegion box="[999,1023,1699,1723]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. Gray) Vail
</taxonomicName>
(CO) and 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1404,1698,1723]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tuberosa">
<emphasis box="[1275,1404,1698,1723]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[1275,1295,1699,1722]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. tuberosa
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (KS). We have also seen mines (including photographs posted to www.BugGuide.net) on 
<taxonomicName box="[1170,1292,1734,1759]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exaltata">
<emphasis box="[1170,1292,1734,1759]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[1170,1191,1735,1758]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. exaltata
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in IA, on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="syriaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[1412,1432,1735,1758]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. syriaca
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in CT, MD, OH, PA, WI, and NB, and on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walter (Spencer" authorityYear="1969" box="[716,820,1770,1795]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridis">
<emphasis box="[716,820,1770,1795]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[716,736,1771,1794]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. viridis
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in OK. These records should be confirmed by rearing, given that two other 
<taxonomicName box="[383,497,1807,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[383,497,1807,1830]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are known to form blotch mines on 
<taxonomicName box="[994,1101,1806,1831]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[994,1101,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Asclepias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Spencer" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1969" box="[1115,1436,1806,1831]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peleensis">
<emphasis box="[1115,1339,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Liriomyza peleensis</emphasis>
Spencer
</taxonomicName>
was reared from 
<taxonomicName box="[341,482,1843,1867]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incarnata">
<emphasis box="[341,482,1843,1867]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[341,361,1843,1866]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. incarnata
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Point Pelee, 
<collectingRegion box="[658,747,1842,1867]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Ontario</collectingRegion>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer (Spencer &amp; Steyskal" authorityYear="1986" box="[806,1001,1842,1867]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subasclepiadis">
<emphasis box="[806,1001,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. subasclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authority="Torr. in Yakima Co." authorityName="Torr. in Yakima Co." box="[1070,1431,1842,1867]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Solidago" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="speciosa">
<emphasis box="[1070,1199,1843,1867]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<collectingRegion box="[1070,1091,1843,1866]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A</collectingRegion>
. speciosa
</emphasis>
Torr. in Yakima Co.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[151,284,1878,1903]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Washington</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[299,457,1878,1903]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[469,758,1878,1903]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal 1986</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation box="[777,949,1878,1903]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer (1969)</bibRefCitation>
stated that numerous larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1969" box="[1303,1436,1878,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peleensis">
<emphasis box="[1303,1436,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. peleensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
feed together in a single leaf, “forming a large blotch with frass scattered irregularly in greenish-black grains”, characterizing those of 
<taxonomicName box="[436,600,1950,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asclepiadis">
<emphasis box="[436,600,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. asclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as “similar, though smaller”. Neither this description nor the single geographic datapoint for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1969" box="[453,593,1986,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peleensis">
<emphasis box="[453,593,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. peleensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seem sufficient to separate the two with confidence. The mine of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer (Spencer &amp; Steyskal" authorityYear="1986" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" order="Diptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subasclepiadis">
<emphasis italics="true" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">L. subasclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described as irregular and interparenchymal, “frequently partially linear, with frass detectable in 2 lines of strips, but often develop[ing] into [a] secondary blotch; mine appears greenish and may be difficult to detect as a true mine” (
<bibRefCitation box="[408,697,223,248]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal 1986</bibRefCitation>
). This largely agrees with our observations of 
<taxonomicName box="[1214,1370,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asclepiadis">
<emphasis box="[1214,1370,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">L. asclepiadis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="Asclepias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="incarnata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<collectingRegion box="[1412,1432,224,247]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">A</collectingRegion>
. incarnata
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the linear portion and strips of frass would be distinctive if present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
